This area acted as a mini sounding to find out more about the area next to the pit and to see if the rocks went further than the bottom of the pit. The rocks did not. The soil did get more dark and ashy near the end of this locus, so we decided to change loci when we dug this part again.
Ended up continuing this locus as a hard packed fill area once the ash pit was defined as a separate locus. Stayed as a locus for over one month but finally ended with everything being brought down to level. Some debate as to whether this locus actually ended up as a wall next to the cobble surface, which is part of the reason we closed the locus and started a new locus
dirt that has collected into chunks

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
